article.description:
Katie Smith scored 28 points, including a key
3-pointer late in the game, and the Minnesota Lynx beat the
Washington Mystics 73-62 on Friday night.
article.headline: Minnesota opens with 18-2 run and holds on
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- After losing most of a 16-point lead in the
first half, the Minnesota Lynx turned to two rookies and an Olympic
veteran.

Katie Smith scored 28 points, including a key 3-pointer late in
the game, and the Lynx beat the Washington Mystics 73-62 in their
home opener Friday night.

The Mystics fell behind early and rallied behind two fast-break
baskets by Coco Miller to cut the lead to 62-56 with 1:40 to play.
On the next possession, Smith launched a 3-pointer from the right
wing that banked in and restored Minnesota's lead to nine points.

"Katie's hit some big shots in her career, and that was huge,"
Minnesota coach Suzie McConnell Serio said. "We talked before the
game about how she needs to be aggressive from the beginning. This
team responds to her, and she gives them confidence."

After falling behind 18-2 in the game's first five minutes, the
Mystics rallied within five at halftime, and when Chamique
Holdsclaw scored the first two baskets of the second half, the
Lynx's lead had shrunk to 33-32.

That's when rookies Amber Jacobs and Tasha Butts came off the
bench to put the clamps on Washington's rally and restore
Minnesota's comfort zone.

Jacobs, who didn't play in the first half, stepped in at point
guard and had four quick assists. She also hit her first shot, a
3-pointer from the corner that stretched Minnesota's lead back to
seven points.

Jacobs later found Butts for consecutive 3-pointers, and when
Butts hit two free throws with 4:33 to play, Minnesota led 60-48.

"That's what we've seen since Day One from those two -- hitting
big shots, playing defense, hustle," Smith said. "I expect that
game in and game out from them."

Minnesota (2-2) was coming off its worst offensive game in
franchise history, a 56-44 loss at San Antonio. But Smith hit two
3-pointers and two free throws, while Nicole Ohlde added three
layups in their game-opening spurt.

But the Lynx let Washington back into the game with some shoddy
ball-handling, committing 23 turnovers, which led to 28 points for
the Mystics (1-3). Holdsclaw, who had 16 points, and Stacy
Dales-Schuman, who had 12, helped Washington scratch its way back,
combining for 13 points to cut the halftime deficit to 33-28.

"That's the way this league is," Smith said. "If you get a
run on somebody to get a big lead, you expect them to make a run
back."

McConnell Serio used veteran Helen Darling to spell point guard
Teresa Edwards in the first half, but when the Mystics continued to
close the gap, she turned to Jacobs for a second-half spark and
found the right mix.

"Basketball is a game of runs, and they got more energy from
their subs than we did," McConnell Serio said. "We need to be
able to pick up where the others left off."
